frameDefinitions: In this frame an Emission emanates from a Source along a Path or to a Goal.
In this frame a Source_emitter discharges its Emission along a Path or to a Goal.  ' (1) The factory exudes toxic fumes from three large chimneys.'
In this frame a Fluid moves from a Source to a Goal along a Path or within an Area.  '
An Agent causes Air to move in a direction, usually specifying either in or out of the body.
This frame covers descriptions of an entire human body, viewed as a gestalt (as opposed to descriptions based on salient body parts).
In this frame a Patient is in a phase brought about after a change of phase.
frameExamples: (1) The factory <t>exudes</t> toxic fumes from three large chimneys.
Collect up the  <t>thawed</t> water from the freezer section.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Emission</fen>s are discharged out of the <fen>Source</fen> .
The <fen>Source</fen> is the location from which the <fen>Emission</fen> emanates.
This role identifies the time when the emanation occurs.
The <fen>Source_emitter</fen> is the item  from which the <fen>Emission</fen> are discharged.
The <fen>Emission</fen>s are discharged out of the <fen>Source_emitter</fen> .
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when  the <fen>Source_emitter</fen> emits the <fen>Emission</fen>.
<fen>Area</fen> is the setting in which the <fen>Fluid</fen>'s movement takes place on an unspecified <fen>Path</fen>.
<fen>Goal</fen> is the location the <fen>Fluid</fen> ends up.
The <fen>Path</fen> is the trajectory along which the <fen>Fluid</fen> moves.
The <fen>Source</fen> is the location the <fen>Fluid</fen> occupies initially.
The <fen>Fluid</fen> is the entity that changes location and moves in a fluidic way.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Fluid</fen> flows.
The Place describes the location of the motion which has a specified Source, Path or Goal.
The <fen>Agent</fen>'s breathing causes the motion of the <fen>Air</fen>.  <fen>Agent</fen> is generally the External Argument.
<fen>Air</fen> is the substance that the <fen>Agent</fen> causes to move.
The time at which breathing occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the breathing occurs.
This role identifies the individual (or individuals) being described.
This role identifies the <fen>Figure</fen> or form being described by the target.
The <fen>Substance</fen> is the entity which has had its phase altered.
listRoleExamples: <fex>At Oregon Caves</fex>, a stream runs through the dining room.
All I know is that he was still breathing <fex>at 2AM</fex>.
Lee breathed with difficulty <fex>on the track</fex>.
